  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Biography of Lady Choi, a Woman of Integrity
  author: Jung Yi-o
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Lady Choi was of the Choi clan, a native of Yongguang County in Jeolla Province who came to dwell in Jinju. Of what generation her family traced back, none could say. She was the daughter of Inyu, Commandant of the Dye Bureau, and the wife of Jeong Man, District Headman of Jinju. Four children were born to her—one still at the breast. In the eighth month of the year Gimmi, the Japanese invaders swept into Jinju, and all the people of the district fled in panic, none daring to resist. At that time, Man was away in the capital on official business. The bandits poured into the quarter where Lady Choi dwelt. She was but thirty-three years of age, and possessed of fair features. Bearing and carrying her children, she fled into the mountains for refuge. The next day, the invaders spread out in all directions, seeking plunder. When they saw Lady Choi, they drew their blades to seize her. She clung to a tree and stood against them, crying out to the brigands: "Death comes to all alike. Better to die with honor than to be defiled by you and live!" Her words poured forth without ceasing. The thieves thrust their swords through her body, and she fell dead beneath the tree. They carried away her ten-year-old daughter and eight-year-old son, then withdrew. Only her six-year-old son remained, standing by her lifeless form. The nursing babe, still at her mother's breast, drank of her blood that flowed like streams, and died likewise. The household servants, who had scattered in flight, returned and gathered the bodies, preparing them for burial and awaiting Man's return. When the year Gisa came, the Provincial Inspector Zhang Ha reported her deeds, and a monument was erected at her gate. Her son Xi was exempted from corvée service.

    The Historian says: When the human heart reaches its ultimate resolve, the upheavals of the world cannot shake it. In such times as these, though a mighty warrior might struggle to choose between life and death, how much more so a single woman? Yet she did not act in ignorance of the invaders' cruelty. Rather, her resolve not to be defiled burned so fiercely in her breast that it outweighed life itself. Now Jiangcheng is the place where steadfast virtue met its end. The mountains grieve, the clouds grow heavy, and the waters weep their lament. Even those who pass by today feel their hair stand on end. Ah, how sublime her integrity!
  footnotes:
    - The year Gimmi (己未) refers to 1619; Gisa (己巳) refers to 1629, marking the posthumous recognition of her virtue.
    - Jiangcheng (江城) is another name for Jinju, the city where Lady Choi met her fate.
    - The historian's final meditation reflects the Confucian virtue of chastity and fidelity, particularly prized in women of the Joseon period.
